🎂 Happy 106th birthday to Bandelier National Monument!

Bandelier protects a number of Native American structures built between 1150 and 1600CE including these incredible cliff dwellings chiseled directly into the volcanic tuff. Tuff is a sedimentary rock composed primarily of volcanic ash, sort of like pumice, from eruptions in the Jemez Mountains between 1.8 and 1.2 million years ago.

image.alt_text: Photo by Taylor’s Beading Galore in Hollister, North Carolina. May be an image of tortoise and outdoors.
image.caption:
As you all know, I was scammed out of $1,000+ dollars for a beadwork set for my Native regalia. Kianga Lucas reached out to me saying a Native artist who was a friend of hers read my post about my scam and wanted to gift me something for all that I went through. Bill Brien, owner of Bountiful Rei’s, gifted me with this duffel bag and an original, hand crafted art piece of my choice. He wanted to gift me something special with hopes that it will help me to heal and I must truly say that this has made me feel better about the situation. They look so much better in person and I am so thankful. 

If you would like to shop his items, his website is: https://bountifulreis.com/shop/

His Instagram is: @bountifulreis

image.alt_text: Photo by James Anaquad Kleinert on February 12, 2022. May be an image of horse, nature and text that says 'James Anaquad Kleinert'.
image.caption:
Mustangs & Renegades The Documentary Series!

On location in New Mexico with Joaquin Gonzalez & Devlin Lara. 

Go to Link Tree below.

>>>> linktr.ee/mustangsnrenegades <<<<

Mustangs & Renegades is a complex web of events woven into the Heart of the American West, documented over a 19 year period. It Follows the True & Personal account of Film Maker James Anaquad Kleinert as he document’s the Round Up & Removal of America’s Wild Horses. In Revealing the plight of our Wild Horses, James shows how our Public Lands are being sold off to the highest bidders exposing the Privatization of Publics lands by the Brutal Multi National Extractive Industries. Exposing how our Constitutional, Environmental and Civil Rights are being Systematically stripped Away! James was quickly targeted by the Department of Interior and their accomplices. The films clearly shows what is happening to journalism in America! James’s FOIA Federal Court Victory - Kleinert vs. Bureau of Land Management, setting Precedent in Freedom Of Information Act Law reveals how DOI is operating. 

This is an epic and honest tale of Activism, Passion and Perseverance that touch the core issues - The Protection of our Natural Environment, Constitutional, Civil and Indigenous Rights! Stunning Cinematography highlighting Wild Horses on Majestic Western Landscapes! This is a film that audiences will resonate deeply with, as our Plight to Protect the Wild Horses mirrors our fight for a Sustainable and Free Future!

image.alt_text: Photo by Butch Is Not A Dirty Word in Santa Fe, New Mexico. May be an image of one or more people and outdoors.
image.full_name: Butch Is Not A Dirty Word
image.caption:
"My Irish grandmother had a conventional view on life - although loving, she actively discouraged my exploration of gender and frequently told me growing up that I couldn't be a tomboy forever, and that one day I'd need to be more ladylike. ⁠
⁠
This was in stark contrast to my Native grandmother's reaction to my gender expression as a child. When I was about 13 years old, she sat me down and told me, “You’re different. For lots of people, that’s not going to be okay, but you’ll get through it, and you’ll be all right”. At the time, I had no idea what she meant by this. She saw something in me that I wasn't aware of yet, but her comforting words took on a new meaning a few years later, as I began to realize I was gay. ⁠
⁠
My Native culture offered me more exploration than I found in the white world - some Native tribes believe that you can choose any life you want; women can be warriors, and men can be homemakers. Not all, but some who choose these alternate paths are Two Spirit." ⁠
⁠
- @ropewolf1, excerpt from: "Between Two Worlds"⁠
⁠
Full essay can be found over at Patreon.com/ButchIsNotADirtyWord⁠
⁠
📸 by @esthergoodboy

image.alt_text: Photo by The 400 Years Project on February 09, 2022. May be an image of footwear.
image.caption:
Photos by @alejandra_rubio_photography (Yavapai-Apache Nation) / Moccasins with “Travel Marks” photographed in my studio.

Hello! I am Alejandra Rubio, a Native American visual artist based in Carson City, Nevada. Over the next week I’ll be sharing images from my “Travel Marks” series. 

I received my first pair of Apache boots when I was 14 and it was the greatest day of my life. These beautiful boots were made and beaded by my grandmother, Elizabeth. I was running for Miss Teen of the Yavapai-Apache Nation and was given the boots along with a beautiful white buckskin dress.

I won the title for Miss Teen, allowing me to travel to other tribes to help represent my nation – and that put a lot of stress on my attire. As for my boots, they were getting too worn out and we didn't have time to repair them. 

When I told my grandmother they were starting to get holes in them, she just smiled and told me, "Those are not holes – those are travel marks. Each mark tells a story of how much you love yourself and your culture. These marks show how much time and effort you have put into your heart for your ancestors. They are very proud of you right now."

image.alt_text: Photo by Native Fans on February 12, 2022. May be a black-and-white image of one or more people, people standing and outdoors.
image.caption:
— June 2, 1924: President Calvin Coolidge on this day signed into law the Indian Citizenship Act, granting full American citizenship to Native-Americans.

Prior to the law, there was some legal ambiguity about whether Native-Americans were citizens by virtue of the Fourteenth Amendment.

A bill granting citizenship was first introduced on August 9, 1919, prompted in part to recognize the participation of thousands of Native-Americans in World War I.

The Indian Civil Rights Act, designed to ensure the civil liberties of individual Native-Americans, was passed by Congress on April 11, 1968.

image: “President Calvin Coolidge with four Osage Indians after Coolidge signed the bill granting Indians full citizenship.” - Library of Congress Prints and Photographs Division, Washington, D.C.

(the Osage Nation is a Midwestern Native American tribe of the Great Plains - Oklahoma, Missouri, Kansas, Arkansas; the tribe developed in the Ohio and Mississippi river valleys around 700 BC along with other groups of its language family)

image.alt_text: Photo by cherokeesiouxs on February 11, 2022. May be an image of text that says 'The holy land is everywhere. 12'.
image.caption:
They say this is the day to go into ceremony with Mother Earth, but if you walk the Red road than everyday we are in ceremony with Mother Earth. I feel and see her love, beauty and her heartbeat every moment in this life i am blessed to live. For we who follow the original instructions shared to us from the one who is greater and handed down to us from our Ancestors, speaks to our heart that we must be grateful and give thanks everyday for the abundance and unconditional love Mother Earth gives us all. Now Mother Earth and all her life that lives upon her skin are having a party without us receiving a invitation, they are the happiest they have ever been not being pushed aside by mans presence, pollution and destruction. We should not dwell on our woes but see the big picture how everything is benefitting on Mother Earth from our absence, for you can see how our needs and freedom come to the expense of all other life. We must be a people that looks through the eyes and can feel from the heart of other life and not just our own, if we want to bring great healing to the sacred hoop..🌎💕🌎

image.alt_text: Photo by SHIKANO HAND MADE on February 05, 2022. May be an image of jewelry.
image.caption:
あれ？これは…大きすぎないかな？という作品たちです。
割と大きめの作品を作りがちです。

先に緻密にデザインを決めたり、デザインをトレースしてからタガネを入れたりする事が少ないので、少し大きめのキャンバスだと安心します。

さらに要因として、100年くらい前の技法、作品に強く影響されているせいもあり、どこか歪で、無骨で、不完全な造形が好きなことも影響しています。
小さな作品でラフな作りをした場合は、ただただチープな雰囲気になる事があるのですが（それはそれでいい場合もあります）、大きくてラフなものは、どこかほっこりするものがある…と勝手に思っています。

誰がつけるんだよ…とか、どこでそんなもん売ってるんだ…？とか、そういうものを作りたいと、ぼんやりと考えています。

image.alt_text: Photo by yübu_abàkütuni(teachings) on February 08, 2022. May be an image of text that says 'I HOPE KNOWING HOW TO SPEAK YOUR NATIVE LANGUAGE IS THE NEXT TREND.'.
image.caption:
@kallinago_aollam

Wakamata akanmbaka wallaom warao. 
Aida liha abuìnchatïna amuìnkali, bwekiniti, anìsjiku. Ahiakàbo aban waollam linyara mhem aida hinhàruyumati wankwa.

We have to learn our native languages.
Knowing this fills me with honor, richness and wisdom. To know one of our languages is to know our true selves.

It also allows you to see how our Ancestors thought and viewed the world.

Our sacred languages, such as Kallìnago, Kallìʔja, Lokono and Garifuna are sacred gifts from the Ichérijum/Sjeminjum. 

These languages hold all of our knowledge and Ancestral power. They hold the knowledge of plant and animal spirits and how to communicate with them. They hold the key to communication with the Itànkumìngu, Ancestors. These are our true languages. 

Kallìnago specifcally holds over 600+ years of unique language, culture and history.

Our Ancestors fought and sacrificed everything to preserve our culture, including the language. We should do the same to preserve it. 

Just as they did, we should be fighting for our Ancestral culture and its survival in every way with equal or greater effort as our Ancestors.

Currently, there are fluent speakers of Lokono, Kallìʔja, and Garifuna, yet younger generations seem uninterested in learning. 

We must put our Ancestral cultures first. Even in the modern world, it is still possible to be authentic and true to Kitànkumìngu and Their* culture.

You can still participate in the modern world while acting/speaking as our Ancestors. You can still eat traditional foods, practice traditional language and spirituality, and do traditional crafts.

*We stress it is Their culture and Their language, not ours. It is only ours to guard, keep and maintain as they did, but it belongs to them.

The importance of language can not be stressed enough. Cultures can not truly heal from colonization without it.

Learning our Ancestral languages should be just as much a priority as learning the other aspects of culture and spirituality. Language contains both of these. 

Currently, Kallìnago is a dead language, meaning there are no fluent speakers. With ample research, respect, and education we can and will grow into a spoken language!

image.alt_text: Photo by indigenousgive on February 11, 2022. May be an image of one or more people.
image.caption:
Kicking Bear and Short Bull. In 1889, Kicking Bear traveled to Nevada to learn the new Ghost Dance religion, then brought it back to his people. The Ghost Dance movement was revived (from an earlier form) in Nevada in the year 1888 by Wovoka, a Paiute Indian mystic and holy man. Performance of the dance was supposed to revive the the native peoples' fortunes and traditions, rejoin them with their ancestors, and return their lands to a pristine state with buffalo and other wildlife in abundance. In addition, the white man would be swallowed up in the earth. The dance was performed by both men and women. Upon Kicking BearÂ’s return, Chief Sitting Bull, Kicking Bear's uncle, asked him to demonstrate the dance at the Standing Rock Reservation in North Dakota, in October 1890. White officials became concerned about the ritual and dispatched police to escort Kicking Bear off the reservation. Nevertheless, Kicking Bear had taught the Ghost Dance to his people. Within two years, the dance would spread over most of the western half of the United States. Just after Christmas in 1890, a shot rang out, and the U.S. Army effectively crippled the Ghost Dance movement among the Lakota when it slaughtered 290 men, women, and children of Chief Big FootÂ’s band, who were being held at a camp along Wounded Knee Creek. The Wounded Knee massacre was the worst domestic atrocity committed by the army in U.S. history. There will be daily posts.

image.caption:
Just because someone stumbles and loses their way, does not mean they will always be lost. We are like the wind and water, where we are gravitated by unseen forces to flow in one direction, one destination. There will be many times in our flowingness that we will be diverted from our true destination, but our heart will always correct this and help us to resume our course. We can easily be influenced by outside forces that for a time we feel is giving us what we need, but truly if it is diverting us from our flowingness and destination than it probably is not good for us. We are only energy like the elements and when you are hollow bones than you are more able to stay on that course because you easily feel the flow of no resistance to oneself. When you have finally learned the most important lessons that are unique to your spirit, and your energy finally flows in least resistance, than you will become a permanent spirit that no longer comes to Mother Earth. You will become a spirit guide for the one who is greater, and you will give your guidance and enlightenment to the lower evolved here on Mother Earth.🌎⭐💕
